\subsection{Ideal-gate decomposition families}
\label{sec:ideal_decomp}

Five gate-family ansatzes were searched using \texttt{UnitarySynthesizer}
at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=4$.
Results are shown in Table~\ref{tab:families} and Fig.~\ref{fig:decomp_tradeoff}.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Best ideal decomposition per gate family (optimized at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=4$).
  Time is total nominal gate time; ``Sel.''\ counts selective blocks (SQR+CPSQR);
  ``Ent.''\ counts entangling blocks (CPSQR+FE).}
\label{tab:families}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccccl@{}}
\toprule
Family & $F$ & Time (ns) & Dep. & Sel./Ent. & Outcome \\
\midrule
$D\!+\!R\!+\!\mathrm{SQR}$ (4 SQR, $t\!=\!3$)
  & \textbf{0.9989} & 4960 & 13 & 4/0 & Successful \\
$D\!+\!R\!+\!\mathrm{SQR}$ (3 SQR, $t\!=\!3$)
  & 0.9944 & 3740 & 10 & 3/0 & Near-target \\
$D\!+\!R\!+\!\mathrm{SQR}\!+\!\mathrm{CPSQR}$
  & 0.9030 & 2913 & 11 & 4/2 & Fam.-limited \\
$D\!+\!\mathrm{SQR}\!+\!\mathrm{CPSQR}$
  & 0.9030 & 4954 & 9  & 6/2 & Fam.-limited \\
$D\!+\!R\!+\!U_{\mathrm{FE}}$
  & 0.8005 & 611  & 11 & 0/3 & Fam.-limited \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The four-SQR family wins on ideal fidelity with $F=0.9989$, using
levels $\{0,1,2\}$ in each selective block (i.e., addressing the lowest
three Fock levels).
The best three-SQR sequence addresses levels $\{0,2,3\}$ and reaches
$F=0.9944$; it is the best \emph{compact} near-solution even though it
does not achieve exact synthesis.
CPSQR-assisted families stall near $F=0.903$ regardless of tone budget,
suggesting they are limited by ansatz expressivity rather than optimization
quality.
The free-evolution family is structurally fast (\SI{611}{ns} total) but
reaches only $F=0.801$, well below the other families.

\begin{figure}[t]
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]
  {../../holographic_cluster_state_ideal_gate_followup/figures/decomposition_tradeoff.pdf}
\caption{Fidelity vs.\ total nominal gate time for the best candidate from
  each ideal-gate family.
  The dashed line marks $F=0.99$; GRAPE points from
  Table~\ref{tab:grape} are shown for reference.}
\label{fig:decomp_tradeoff}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Explicit test of the three-SQR hypothesis}
\label{sec:three_sqr}

The three-SQR branch was treated as a primary research question:
is three SQR blocks sufficient for exact synthesis of $U_{\mathrm{target}}$?
Figure~\ref{fig:three_sqr} shows the best ideal fidelity as a function
of \texttt{max\_tones}.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]
  {../../holographic_cluster_state_ideal_gate_followup/figures/three_sqr_tone_budget.pdf}
\caption{Best ideal fidelity of the three-SQR ansatz as a function of the
  tone budget \texttt{max\_tones}. The jump from $2\to 3$ tones shows that
  the earlier two-tone saturation was an artificial search restriction,
  not a fundamental expressivity boundary.}
\label{fig:three_sqr}
\end{figure}

The best fidelities per tone budget are
$0.9382$ (\texttt{max\_tones}$=1$),
$0.9704$ (\texttt{max\_tones}$=2$),
$0.9944$ (\texttt{max\_tones}$=3$),
and $0.9557$ (\texttt{max\_tones}$=4$).
Two observations stand out.
First, the regression at four tones ($0.9557 < 0.9944$) is more likely an
optimization-landscape artifact than a fundamental loss of expressivity;
the parameter space is substantially larger and the search budget was fixed.
Second, the three-SQR hypothesis was not \emph{disproved}: the near-target
$0.9944$ result could in principle be improved further with a larger
optimization budget or a better initialization strategy.
However, it was not established as \emph{sufficient} either, since the
gap from $0.9944$ to $1.0000$ was not closed.

\subsection{Physical validation of GRAPE candidates}
\label{sec:validation}

The GRAPE benchmark at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8$ is not a final physical verdict.
Table~\ref{tab:validation} summarizes the truncation-convergence probe and
physical replay results.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Truncation convergence and replay fidelities for GRAPE waveforms.
  ``Replay'' denotes re-simulation at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=12$;
  ``open'' is the Lindblad process fidelity.}
\label{tab:validation}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lcccc@{}}
\toprule
Duration & $F$ (N8) & $F$ (N10) & $F$ (N12) & $F_{\mathrm{open}}$ \\
\midrule
200 ns (best seed) & 0.9902 & $\approx0.95$ & $\approx0.95$ & --- \\
300 ns (best seed) & 0.99997 & degraded & degraded & --- \\
400 ns (best seed) & 0.99975 & --- & 0.956 & 0.901 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Two points from the validation are important.
First, the \SI{300}{ns} best seed is extremely strong at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8$
but degrades noticeably at larger truncations, meaning the benchmark should
not be taken as a converged physical result.
Second, the \SI{400}{ns} waveform from the \emph{direct} $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=12$
GRAPE pass (not the $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8$ benchmark) achieves replay fidelity
$0.956$ and open-system process fidelity $0.901$, establishing it as the
only physically credible high-fidelity route in this study.
Early $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8$ GRAPE solutions, when replayed at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=12$,
dropped to $F_{\mathrm{replay}} \approx 0.12$, demonstrating that training
truncation matters critically for physical predictions.

\subsection{Comparison: GRAPE vs.\ ideal decomposition}
\label{sec:comparison}

Figure~\ref{fig:grape_vs_decomp} places the best ideal decomposition and the
GRAPE frontier on the same axes.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]
  {../../holographic_cluster_state_ideal_gate_followup/figures/grape_vs_best_decomposition.pdf}
\caption{Best ideal decomposition (four-SQR / three-tone, $F=0.9989$,
  \SI{4960}{ns}) versus the GRAPE benchmark frontier.
  GRAPE crosses $F=0.9989$ between \SI{200}{ns} and \SI{250}{ns},
  and reaches $F>0.9999$ by \SI{300}{ns}.}
\label{fig:grape_vs_decomp}
\end{figure}

The comparison is unambiguous: GRAPE crosses the fidelity achieved by the
best ideal decomposition between \SI{200}{ns} and \SI{250}{ns} in total gate
time, while the decomposition requires \SI{4960}{ns}.
The ideal decomposition is therefore slower by a factor of approximately $16$--$25$
at the same fidelity level.

This does not mean that the ideal decomposition is useless.
Structured gate sequences have interpretability advantages (every gate has
a physical motivation), they can serve as initial guesses for pulse
refinement, and they may be more robust to certain systematic errors.
But for raw gate speed or for targets where protocol fidelity must exceed
$0.999$, direct GRAPE is the better strategy.

%% ---------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
%% ---------------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{What does and does not work}

The clearest take-away is that \textbf{Hilbert-space truncation must be
validated}. Any synthesis result reported at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=2$ should be
treated as a hypothesis, not a result, until confirmed at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}\geq 8$.
The failure mode is subtle because a small truncation can make sequences
appear exact by cutting off the leakage: the simulator reports perfect
fidelity on the logical subspace simply because the population that leaked
into high Fock levels was truncated away.

The bounded-displacement fix is a partial remedy: it reduces leakage but
simultaneously reduces the available Hilbert-space reach, leading to a
fidelity ceiling below any useful threshold.

\subsection{The right synthesis strategy for different goals}

The three strategies below address distinct experimental priorities.
Table~\ref{tab:strategy} provides a concise comparison.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Strategy comparison at a glance.
  $F_\mathrm{id}$: ideal fidelity.
  $F_\mathrm{phys}$: physically validated fidelity (replay or open-system).}
\label{tab:strategy}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lcccl@{}}
\toprule
Strategy & $F_\mathrm{id}$ & Time & $F_\mathrm{phys}$ & Priority \\
\midrule
GRAPE / $N_{\mathrm{cav}}\geq 12$   & ---    & \SI{400}{ns} & 0.956 & Speed/fidelity \\
4-SQR / 3-tone                       & 0.9989 & \SI{4960}{ns} & --- & Interpretability \\
3-SQR / 3-tone                       & 0.9944 & \SI{3740}{ns} & --- & Compact near-sol. \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Minimum gate time / highest fidelity.}
Direct GRAPE at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}\geq 12$ is the recommended route.
The physically validated result achieves $F_{\mathrm{replay}}=0.956$ and
$F_{\mathrm{open}}=0.901$ at \SI{400}{ns} (see Appendix~\ref{app:states} for
the corresponding output-state observables).
The $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8$ closed benchmark suggests $F>0.999$ may be reachable
at \SI{300}{ns}, but any waveform optimized at that truncation must be
re-validated at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=12$ before being treated as a physical result.
The expected output states are listed in Appendix~\ref{app:states}: each logical
input maps to a cavity superposition state with a definite transmon polarization
(Fig.~\ref{fig:obs}), and the target cavity Wigner functions exhibit interference
fringes (Fig.~\ref{fig:wigner}) that directly confirm entanglement generation.

\paragraph{Structured / interpretable gate sequence.}
The four-SQR / three-tone decomposition ($F=0.9989$, total time \SI{4960}{ns},
depth 13) is the best systematically derived ideal-gate sequence.
Its structure makes every gate step physically interpretable:
displacements inject coherent amplitude into the cavity; qubit rotations set
the superposition axis; selective qubit rotations at Fock levels $\{0,1,2\}$
imprint level-dependent phases that generate entanglement between qubit and
cavity over the four repetitions.
This sequence is stable under ideal truncation enlargement ($F=0.9900$ at
$N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8$, average leakage $\approx 2\%$), making it a reliable
reference solution and a natural warm-start candidate for GRAPE refinement.

\paragraph{Compact near-solution.}
The three-SQR / three-tone ansatz ($F=0.9944$, \SI{3740}{ns}) requires
three instead of four SQR blocks and is $25\%$ shorter in total gate time.
It remains an incomplete result: the optimization has not closed the gap to
exact synthesis, and the sequence degrades sharply to $F\approx 0.79$ at
$N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8$ (ideal), indicating non-trivial leakage that would
worsen under physical truncation.
It is best used as a starting point for a dedicated higher-budget optimization
or a formal expressivity analysis of the three-SQR family.

\subsection{Open questions}

The three-SQR hypothesis remains open: neither sufficiency nor insufficiency
was established. Addressing this would require a denser search over level
subsets and initializations, or a formal circuit expressivity argument.

The GRAPE truncation probe suggests that $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8$ is not
always sufficient for a converged benchmark; a systematic convergence study
comparing $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8, 10, 12$ across all durations would be valuable.

Finally, the ideal decomposition results are purely ideal (zero decoherence).
Incorporating the dispersive drift into the SQR timing---which is already
done for CPSQR blocks in the current framework---would provide a more
physical ideal-gate fidelity for the SQR-heavy decompositions.

%% ---------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Conclusions}
\label{sec:conclusions}
%% ---------------------------------------------------------------

This study consolidates three iterative investigations of holographic
cluster-state synthesis in a dispersive transmon-cavity system into a single
coherent account. The main conclusions are:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Truncation artifacts are the dominant failure mode} for
    compact gate decompositions. Any sequence claiming exact fidelity at
    $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=2$ must be validated at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}\geq 8$.
  \item \textbf{The only physically validated high-fidelity implementation}
    is direct GRAPE at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}\geq 12$:
    $F_{\mathrm{replay}}=0.956$, $F_{\mathrm{open}}=0.901$ at \SI{400}{ns}.
  \item \textbf{GRAPE speed frontier}: $F>0.95$ by \SI{150}{ns},
    $F>0.99$ by \SI{200}{ns}, $F>0.9999$ by \SI{300}{ns} (at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8$;
    larger truncations may require longer durations).
  \item \textbf{Best ideal-gate decomposition}: four-SQR / three-tone,
    $F=0.9989$, \SI{4960}{ns}, depth 13. This is over $16\times$ slower
    than the GRAPE benchmark at equivalent fidelity.
  \item \textbf{Three-SQR hypothesis}: best result $F=0.9944$ at
    \texttt{max\_tones}$=3$; neither provably sufficient nor insufficient.
    Earlier saturation at \texttt{max\_tones}$=2$ was an artificial search limit.
  \item \textbf{CPSQR/FE families are family-limited}: both stall well below
    the four-SQR result ($F\leq 0.903$ and $F\leq 0.801$ respectively)
    and are unlikely to be rescued by more optimization.
\end{enumerate}

For a research program targeting high-fidelity cluster-state generation,
the recommended strategy is direct GRAPE optimization at $N_{\mathrm{cav}}\geq 12$
with waveform replay validation, targeting the \SIrange{200}{300}{ns} duration
range for optimal speed-fidelity trade-off. Ideal-gate decompositions are
valuable as structured reference solutions and potential GRAPE warm starts,
but they do not compete with direct optimal control in raw performance.

