\section{Target Output States: Qubit and Cavity Observables}
\label{app:states}

This appendix documents the exact quantum states produced by
$U_{\mathrm{target}} = \mathrm{SWAP}\cdot\mathrm{CZ}\cdot(H\otimes I)$
for each of the four computational-basis inputs.
These serve as the ground truth against which any experimental or numerical
implementation should be compared.

\subsection{Analytical output states}
\label{app:analytic}

In the ordered basis $\{\ket{g,0},\ket{g,1},\ket{e,0},\ket{e,1}\}$ the target
maps each logical input to a product state in the transmon and a superposition
in the cavity logical qubit:
\begin{align}
U_{\mathrm{target}}\ket{g,0} &=
  \ket{g}\otimes\frac{\ket{0}+\ket{1}}{\sqrt{2}}, \label{eq:out_g0}\\
U_{\mathrm{target}}\ket{g,1} &=
  \ket{e}\otimes\frac{\ket{0}-\ket{1}}{\sqrt{2}}, \label{eq:out_g1}\\
U_{\mathrm{target}}\ket{e,0} &=
  \ket{g}\otimes\frac{\ket{0}-\ket{1}}{\sqrt{2}}, \label{eq:out_e0}\\
U_{\mathrm{target}}\ket{e,1} &=
  \ket{e}\otimes\frac{\ket{0}+\ket{1}}{\sqrt{2}}. \label{eq:out_e1}
\end{align}
In every case the transmon factorizes from the cavity after the gate:
inputs with even parity ($\ket{g,0}$ and $\ket{e,1}$) map the cavity to
$(\ket{0}+\ket{1})/\sqrt{2}$; inputs with odd parity
($\ket{g,1}$ and $\ket{e,0}$) map the cavity to
$(\ket{0}-\ket{1})/\sqrt{2}$.
The transmon is deterministically polarized to $\ket{g}$ or $\ket{e}$
depending on the input cavity occupation.

\subsection{Transmon Bloch-vector components and cavity populations}

Figure~\ref{fig:obs} shows the transmon Bloch-vector expectation values
$\langle X\rangle$, $\langle Y\rangle$, $\langle Z\rangle$ and the cavity
Fock populations $P(n=0)$, $P(n=1)$ for all four target output states,
computed from Eqs.~\eqref{eq:out_g0}--\eqref{eq:out_e1}.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{../figures/appendix_state_observables.pdf}
\caption{Target output-state observables computed analytically from
  $U_{\mathrm{target}}$.
  \emph{Left:} transmon Bloch-vector components for each logical input.
  $\langle X\rangle = \langle Y\rangle = 0$ for all inputs; only
  $\langle Z\rangle = \pm 1$ is non-zero, confirming the transmon
  is fully polarized after the gate.
  \emph{Right:} cavity Fock populations, showing equal $P(n=0)=P(n=1)=0.5$
  in all cases, consistent with the $(\ket{0}\pm\ket{1})/\sqrt{2}$ cavity
  output states.}
\label{fig:obs}
\end{figure}

Key signatures for experimental or numerical verification:
\begin{itemize}
  \item The transmon should satisfy $|\langle Z\rangle|=1$ and
    $\langle X\rangle=\langle Y\rangle=0$ after the gate.
    Any deviation indicates residual qubit-cavity entanglement or leakage.
  \item The cavity Fock populations should be equal: $P(0)=P(1)=0.5$.
    An imbalance directly measures the failure of the displacement / rotation
    steps to create an equal superposition.
  \item The off-diagonal coherence $\langle a+a^\dagger\rangle
    = \mathrm{Re}\langle\alpha\rangle$ should be $\pm 1/\sqrt{2}$, with
    the sign distinguishing $(\ket{0}+\ket{1})/\sqrt{2}$ from
    $(\ket{0}-\ket{1})/\sqrt{2}$.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Cavity Wigner functions}

Figure~\ref{fig:wigner} shows the cavity Wigner function
\begin{equation}
W(\alpha) = \frac{2}{\pi}\,\mathrm{Tr}
  \bigl[\hat{\rho}_{\mathrm{cav}}\,D(\alpha)\,(-1)^{a^\dagger a}\,D^\dagger(\alpha)\bigr]
\end{equation}
for each logical input sector.
The left column is the target Wigner function from
Eqs.~\eqref{eq:out_g0}--\eqref{eq:out_e1};
the right column is the Wigner function achieved by Strategy~B
($D+\mathrm{SQR}+\mathrm{CP}$, two blocks, $N_{\mathrm{cav}}=8$)
from the initial study.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{../figures/appendix_wigner.pdf}
\caption{Cavity Wigner functions per logical input sector.
  \emph{Left column:} target $W(\alpha)$, exhibiting the characteristic
  interference fringes (negative regions near $\mathrm{Re}\,\alpha=0$)
  of the $(\ket{0}\pm\ket{1})/\sqrt{2}$ superposition states.
  \emph{Right column:} Strategy~B achieved Wigner function.
  The large mismatch and the absence of negative values in the
  $\ket{g,0}$ sector (cavity fidelity 0.884) and the qualitative
  failure in $\ket{g,1}$ (cavity fidelity 0.544) confirm that
  Strategy~B does not physically prepare the correct cavity state
  despite its apparent ideal-subspace fidelity.
  Cavity fidelity values: 0.884, 0.544, 0.815, 0.499
  for $\ket{g,0}$, $\ket{g,1}$, $\ket{e,0}$, $\ket{e,1}$, respectively.}
\label{fig:wigner}
\end{figure}

The interference fringes visible in the target Wigner functions are the
hallmark of the non-classical superposition created by the gate.
Their absence or deformation in the Strategy~B panels directly reflects
the truncation-induced leakage: population displaced into Fock levels
$n\geq 2$ contributes to decoherence of the logical $\ket{0}/\ket{1}$
superposition, washing out the fringes.
This visual comparison makes the physical failure of native decompositions
concrete, and motivates the use of GRAPE with $N_{\mathrm{cav}}\geq 12$
as the only currently validated route to the correct cavity state.

